[]: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Quote Post by Reichu &raquo; Tue Mar 04, 2008 5:34 pm Oh, thing is, when you&#39;re dealing with image files, the rule is to do all editing BEFORE the file goes into a compressed format, namely JPEG, in the first place. JPEGs are full of ugly compression artifacts -- extent and visibility depends on degree of compression -- and they&#39;re essentially being compressed again every time they&#39;re saved, providing an additive degenerative effect. Your files already have, at their default magnification, huge artifacts that are visible to the naked eye, which is, in grunty-speak, a &quot;VERY BAD THING!&quot;. Unless you still have original, uncompressed PNGs &#40;or whatever&#41; of your scans lying around, they&#39;re only going to look worse from here on out.

